t \\(\\overline{AB}\\) can also be named \\(\\overline{BA}\\).\n\n\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\\centering\n\t\\includegraphics[width=0.4\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/segment.pdf}\n\t\\caption*{segment \\(\\overline{AB}\\) or \\(\\overline{BA}\\)}\n\\end{figure}\n\n\\textbf{Ray}: The ray \\(AB\\) (written as \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\)) consists of\nthe point \\(A\\) and all points on \\(\\overleftrightarrow{AB}\\) that lie on the\nsame side of \\(A\\) as \\(B\\).\n\nNote that \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{BA}\\) are different rays.\n\n\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\\centering\n\t\\includegraphics[width=0.4\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/ray.pdf}\n\t\\caption*{rays $\\overrightarrow{AB}$ and $\\overrightarrow{BA}$}\n\\end{figure}\n\n\\textbf{Opposite rays}: If point \\(C\\) lies on \\(\\overleftrightarrow{AB}\\) between\n\\(A\\) and \\(B\\), then \\(\\overrightarrow{CA}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{CB}\\)\nare opposite rays.\n\n\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\\centering\n\t\\includegraphics[width=0.5\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/opposite-rays.pdf}\n\t\\caption*{opposite rays \\(\\overrightarrow{CA}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{CB}\\)}\n\\end{figure}\n\nSegments and rays are collinear if they lie on the same line. So, opposite rays\nare collinear. Lines, segments, and rays are coplanar if they lie in the\nsame plane.\n\n\\begin{example}\n\tName segments, rays, and opposite rays\n\n\t\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\t\\centering\n\t\t\\includegraphics[width=0.4\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/example-2.pdf}\n\t\\end{figure}\n\n\t\\begin{enumerate}\n\t\t\\item Give another name for \\(\\overline{GH}\\).\n\n\t\t\\item Name all rays with endpoint \\(J\\). Which of these rays are opposite rays?\n\n\t\t\\item Give another name for \\(\\overline{EF}\\).\n\n\t\t\\item Are \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{JH}\\)\n\t\t      the same ray? Are \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\)\n\t\t      and \\(\\overrightarrow{HG}\\) the same ray?\n\t\\end{enumerate}\n\n\t\\begin{solution}\n\t\t\\begin{enumerate}\n\t\t\t\\item Another name for \\(\\overrightarrow{GH}\\) is \\(\\overrightarrow{HG}\\).\n\n\t\t\t\\item The rays with endpoint \\(J\\) are \\(\\overrightarrow{JE}\\),\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{JG}\\), \\(\\overrightarrow{JF}\\), and\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{JH}\\).\n\n\t\t\t      The pairs of opposite rays with endpoint \\(J\\) are \\(\\overrightarrow{JE}\\)\n\t\t\t      and \\(\\overrightarrow{JF}\\), and \\(\\overrightarrow{JG}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{JH}\\).\n\n\t\t\t\\item Another name for \\(\\overline{EF}\\) is \\(\\overline{FE}\\).\n\n\t\t\t\\item \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{JH}\\) are not the same rays.\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\) includes the endpoint \\(H\\) and the points on\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overleftrightarrow{HJ}\\) that lie on the same side as point \\(J\\) while\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{JH}\\) includes the endpoint \\(J\\) and the points that lie on\n\t\t\t      the same side as point \\(H\\).\n\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{HG}\\) are the same rays\n\t\t\t      since they both contain the endpoint \\(H\\) and all the points of the line\n\t\t\t      \\(\\overrightarrow{HJ}\\) that lie on the same side as point \\(J\\).\n\n\t\t\\end{enumerate}\n\t\\end{solution}\n\\end{example}\n\n\\subsection{Intersections}\n\n\\textbf{Intersection}: Two or more geometric figures intersect if they have one or\nmore points in common. The intersection of the figures is the set of points\nthe figures have in common. Some examples of intersections are\nshown below.\n\n\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\\centering\n\t\\includegraphics[width=0.4\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/intersection-lines.pdf}\n\t\\caption*{The intersection of two different lines is a point.}\n\\end{figure}\n\n\\begin{figure}[H]\n\t\\centering\n\t\\includegraphics[width=0.4\\textwidth]{figures/chapter-1/intersection-planes.pdf}\n\t\\caption*{The intersection of two different planes is a line.}\n\\end{figure}